Angels in Christianity are, by their very nature, more than just ethereal beings delivering divine pronouncements. They are the conduits of [God](/God_in_Christianity)'s will, acting as His messengers, yes, but also as steadfast protectors, unwavering guides, and diligent servants. Their presence permeates the entirety of the [Christian Bible](/Bible), weaving through narratives of divine intervention in the affairs of humankind. They are depicted in constant [worship of God](/Christian_worship), offering eternal praise, and are tasked with guarding both individual souls and entire nations. Christian theology, in its intricate tapestry, often emphasizes their role as intermediaries, bridging the infinite chasm between the divine and the mortal, and delineates their existence within a complex, ordered structure of [hierarchical ranks](/Hierarchy_of_angels), such as the exalted [seraphim](/Seraph) and the ever-watchful [guardian angels](/Guardian_Angel).

