In the grand narrative of [Christianity](/Christianity), [angels](/Angel) are far more than mere celestial ornaments. They are the very messengers of [God](/God_in_Christianity), fulfilling diverse and crucial roles throughout the sacred texts of the [Christian Bible](/Bible). While their primary function is indeed to convey divine messages, their influence extends to acting as counselors and guides, offering wisdom and direction across both the [Old Testament](/Old_Testament) and the [New Testament](/New_Testament).

### In the Bible

The [Psalms](/Book_of_Psalms), specifically Psalm 91:11–12, explicitly attributes the [guardianship](/Guardian_Angel) of humanity to these celestial beings. &#91;1&#93; It’s a comforting thought, if you’re inclined to find comfort in such things.

In the Gospel of [Matthew](/Gospel_of_Matthew) 18:10, Jesus himself offers a profound insight, cautioning against despising the innocence of children by stating, "their angels in [heaven](/Heaven) always see the [face](/Face_of_God) of my [Father](/God_the_Father) in heaven." This suggests a constant, intimate connection between the celestial and the earthly. Furthermore, Luke 20:34–36 reinforces this, affirming that those deemed worthy of the age to come and the [resurrection from the dead](/Resurrection_of_the_flesh) will exist in a state akin to the angels, neither marrying nor being given in marriage, and beyond the reach of death.

### General views

#### Antiquity

*   This section, I must point out, is desperately in need of some substance. It hints at a "general view of angels according to Christians in Antiquity" but provides little more than a whisper. It requires significant expansion to offer any real insight. You can, of course, help by adding to it. (February 2023)

During the nascent stages of Christian thought, figures like [Ignatius of Antioch](/Ignatius_of_Antioch), in chapter V of his Letter to the Trallians, presented a conceptualization of angels that bore a striking resemblance to the later, more formalized hierarchies proposed by Pseudo-Dionysius. Even [Clement of Rome](/Clement_of_Rome), in his [First Epistle of Clement](/First_Epistle_of_Clement), urged his listeners to emulate the angels in their unwavering praise of God. The intellectual tapestry of [Clement of Alexandria](/Clement_of_Alexandria) suggested a more immanent role for angels, positing that they "breathe" inspiration into human thoughts and reasonings, and infuse the heart with "strength" and enhanced perception. &#91;2&#93;

[Evagrius Ponticus](/Evagrius_Ponticus), a mystic and theologian, explored the concept of angelic companions, viewing angels not just as distant entities but as models for human behavior and spiritual aspiration. &#91;3&#93;

Even [Augustine of Hippo](/Augustine_of_Hippo), a towering figure in Christian thought, contemplated the angels' experience of the unfolding [creation of God](/Genesis_creation_narrative). He noted that the angels themselves were encountering novelty as the cosmos came into being. &#91;4&#93; Augustine also articulated the belief that the 'good' angels consistently strive to guide humanity toward [God](/God_in_Christianity), the ultimate source of all happiness, and to inspire us in our [Christian worship](/Christian_worship). &#91;5&#93;

#### Pseudo-Dionysian hierarchy

*   Main article: [De Coelesti Hierarchia](/De_Coelesti_Hierarchia)
*   Further information: [Hierarchy of angels](/Hierarchy_of_angels)

The most enduring and influential framework for understanding the angelic realm within Christianity originates from [Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite](/Pseudo-Dionysius_the_Areopagite) and his seminal work, [De Coelesti Hierarchia](/De_Coelesti_Hierarchia) ( *On the Celestial Hierarchy* ). This text, dating from around the turn of the 6th century CE, posits a meticulously structured universe of angels, divided into three distinct levels, or "spheres," with each sphere containing three specific orders.

The Pseudo-Dionysius, a figure who claimed to have been converted by no less than [Paul the Apostle](/Paul_the_Apostle), wielded considerable authority. His actual identity remained a subject of scholarly debate until the early 16th century when [Erasmus](/Erasmus) publicly questioned the antiquity of his writings, a revelation that somewhat tempered his unquestioned influence. &#91;6&#93;

##### Catholic Church

The official stance of the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) on angels is clearly articulated within the [Catechism of the Catholic Church](/Catechism_of_the_Catholic_Church). Paragraph 328 states unequivocally that "the existence of the spiritual, non-corporeal beings that [Sacred Scripture](/Catholic_Bible) usually calls 'angels' is [a truth of faith](/Dogma_in_the_Catholic_Church). The witness of Scripture is as clear as the unanimity of [Tradition](/Sacred_tradition)." &#91;7&#93; The same [catechism](/Catechism) further elaborates on their active role in human life, asserting that "the whole life of the church benefits from the mysterious and powerful help of the angels [...] From its beginning until death, human life is surrounded by their watchful care and intercession." &#91;8&#93; It also emphasizes Christ's central position in the angelic realm: "Christ is the center of the angelic world. They are His angels [...] They belong to Him because they were created through and for Him." &#91;9&#93;

##### The New Church (Swedenborgianism)

Within the denominations that trace their theological roots to the writings of [Emanuel Swedenborg](/Emanuel_Swedenborg), the understanding of angels and their spiritual domain takes a unique turn. Adherents of [The New Church](/The_New_Church_(Swedenborgian)) believe that all angels possess a human form, albeit with a spiritual body, and are not merely disembodied intellects. &#91;10&#93; These celestial beings are organized into different orders corresponding to the three distinct heavens, &#91;11&#93; and each angel resides within one of countless angelic societies. These societies, when viewed collectively, can manifest as a singular angelic form. &#91;12&#93;

A fundamental tenet of Swedenborgian angelology is that all angels originate from the human race; there is not a single angel in heaven who has not, at some point, inhabited a physical body on Earth. &#91;13&#93; Consequently, it is believed that all children who die are welcomed into heaven and eventually mature into angelic beings. &#91;14&#93; The life of angels is characterized by perpetual usefulness, their functions so numerous and varied that they defy complete enumeration. Each angel assumes a role that directly reflects the purpose and utility they demonstrated during their earthly existence. &#91;15&#93; Moreover, the names of prominent angels, such as Michael, Gabriel, and Raphael, are understood not to denote unique individuals but rather to signify specific angelic functions or roles. &#91;16&#93;

During earthly life, individuals maintain a connection with the heavens through these angelic intermediaries, &#91;17&#93; and it is believed that each person is accompanied by at least two malevolent spirits and two benevolent angels. &#91;18&#93; Experiences of temptation or pangs of conscience are attributed to the internal conflict between these opposing spiritual forces. &#91;19&#93; Due to the inherent sinfulness of human nature, direct, unmediated communication with angels is considered perilous, &#91;20&#93; and they can only be perceived when one's spiritual vision is opened. &#91;21&#93; Thus, angels subtly guide individuals toward goodness by working through their own thoughts, guiding them tacitly from moment to moment. &#91;22&#93;

##### Latter Day Saint movement

The [Latter Day Saint movement](/Latter_Day_Saint_movement), often referred to as Mormonism, shares the view of angels as divine messengers. They are believed to be dispatched by God to deliver critical messages, minister to humanity's needs, impart the doctrines of salvation, call individuals to repentance, bestow [priesthood](/Priesthood_(LDS_Church)) authority and keys, rescue people from perilous situations, and provide guidance to humankind. &#91;23&#93;

Latter-day Saints hold that angels are either the spirits of deceased humans, spirits who [have yet to be born](/Pre-existence), or beings who have undergone [resurrection](/Resurrection) or [translation](/Translation_(Mormonism)) and thus possess tangible bodies of flesh and bone. &#91;24&#93; [Joseph Smith](/Joseph_Smith), the movement's founder, taught that "there are no angels who minister to this earth but those that do belong or have belonged to it." &#91;25&#93; This belief leads to the understanding that [Adam](/Adam_and_Eve_(LDS_Church)), the first man, was and still is the archangel [Michael](/Michael_(archangel)), &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93; and that [Gabriel](/Gabriel) lived on Earth in the person of [Noah](/Noah). &#91;24&#93; Similarly, the [Angel Moroni](/Angel_Moroni), a key figure in Latter-day Saint belief, is understood to have first lived as a prophet-warrior named [Moroni](/Moroni_(Book_of_Mormon_prophet)) in a [pre-Columbian American civilization](/Nephite) during the 5th century.

Smith himself recounted his initial angelic encounter with vivid detail:

> While I was thus in the act of calling upon God, I discovered a light appearing in my room, which continued to increase until the room was lighter than at noonday, when immediately a personage appeared at my bedside, standing in the air, for his feet did not touch the floor.
>
> He had on a loose robe of most exquisite whiteness. It was a whiteness beyond anything earthly I had ever seen; nor do I believe that any earthly thing could be made to appear so exceedingly white and brilliant...
>
> Not only was his robe exceedingly white, but his whole person was glorious beyond description, and his countenance truly like lightning. The room was exceedingly light, but not so very bright as immediately around his person. When I first looked upon him, I was afraid; but the fear soon left me. &#91;29&#93;

A significant number of angelic visitations reported during the early days of the Latter Day Saint movement were witnessed by Smith and [Oliver Cowdery](/Oliver_Cowdery). Prior to the official establishment of the church in 1830, both men claimed to have been visited by the prophet [Moroni](/Angel_Moroni), [John the Baptist](/John_the_Baptist), and the apostles [Peter](/Saint_Peter), [James,_son_of_Zebedee], and [John the Apostle](/John_the_Apostle). Later, following the dedication of the [Kirtland Temple](/Kirtland_Temple), Smith and Cowdery asserted that they had been visited by [Jesus](/Jesus) himself, and subsequently by [Moses](/Moses), Elias, and [Elijah]. &#91;30&#93;

Other prominent figures who claimed angelic visitations include two of the [Three Witnesses](/Three_Witnesses) to the Book of Mormon: [David Whitmer](/David_Whitmer) and [Martin Harris](/Martin_Harris_(Latter_Day_Saints)). Throughout the history of the Church, both in its early period and in modern times, numerous other Latter-day Saints have reported seeing angels. However, Smith also posited a principle of angelic ministration: that, barring exceptional circumstances such as the [restoration](/Restoration_(Latter_Day_Saints)) of the gospel, mortals primarily teach mortals, spirits teach spirits, and resurrected beings instruct other resurrected beings. &#91;31&#93;

### Catholic angel hierarchy

An Eastern [icon](/Icon) meticulously illustrates the nine orders of angels.
A [cherub](/Cherub), as described by the prophet [Ezekiel](/Ezekiel) and rendered according to traditional Christian [iconography](/Iconography).
The Archangel Michael vanquishing Satan, a dramatic depiction by [Guido Reni](/Guido_Reni) from 1636, which adorns the Capuchin church of [Santa Maria della Concezione, Rome](/Santa_Maria_della_Concezione,_Rome).
The west window of the [Church of St Michael and All Angels, Somerton](/Church_of_St_Michael_and_All_Angels,_Somerton) presents a visual representation of celestial authority. At its center is [Christ the King](/Christ_the_King), flanked by nine angelic figures, each symbolizing a distinct rank: in the upper row, [Dominions](/Dominions_(angel)), [Cherubim](/Cherub), [Seraphim](/Seraph), and [Angels](/Angel); in the lower row, [Principalities](/Principalities_(angel)), [Thrones](/Throne_(angel)), [Archangels](/Archangel), [Virtues](/Virtues_(angel)), and [Powers](/Powers_(angel)).

#### First Order

##### Seraphim

*   Main article: [Seraph](/Seraph)

Within the intricate framework of Christian angelology, tradition places the [seraphim](/Seraph) at the very pinnacle of the angelic ranks, drawing inspiration from the prophet [Isaiah](/Isaiah)'s powerful use of the term. These are the angels closest to [God](/God_in_Christianity), charged with leading the heavenly host in perpetual worship, their voices raised in endless, ecstatic praise. &#91;32&#93;

##### Cherubim

*   Main article: [Cherub](/Cherub)

The description of the [cherub](/Cherub) in the [Book of Ezekiel](/Book_of_Ezekiel), and its subsequent interpretation in certain Christian icons, presents a complex being. It is depicted with two pairs of wings and four distinct faces: that of a [lion](/Lion) (representing all [wild animals](/Wild_animals)), an [ox](/Ox) (symbolizing [domestic animals](/Domestic_animals)), a [human](/Human) (standing for humanity), and an [eagle](/Eagle) (representing [birds](/Bird)). &#91;33&#93; Their legs are described as straight, with the soles of their feet resembling the hooves of a bull, all gleaming with the brilliance of polished brass. Later traditions have assigned a variety of physical appearances to the cherubim. &#91;33&#93; In the Western Christian tradition, the cherubim have undergone a significant transformation in popular imagination, often becoming conflated with the [putto] (derived from the classical figures of [Cupid](/Cupid)/[Eros]), resulting in their common depiction as small, plump, winged infants. &#91;34&#93;

##### Thrones or Ophanim

*   Main articles: [Throne (angel)](/Throne_(angel)) and [Ophanim](/Ophanim)

The [ophanim](/Ophanim) are a class of celestial beings associated with the wheels observed in [Ezekiel](/Ezekiel)'s visionary account of the divine chariot, or [merkabah](/Merkabah), in Ezekiel 1:15–21. Intriguingly, one of the [Dead Sea scrolls](/Dead_Sea_scrolls) (specifically, 4Q405) interprets these wheels as angelic entities. &#91;35&#93;

#### Second Order

##### Dominions or Lordships

*   Main article: [Dominion (angel)](/Dominion_(angel))

The Dominions, known in Latin as *dominationes* and derived from the Greek *kyriotētes* (meaning "Lordships"), &#91;36&#93; are traditionally understood to be responsible for governing the celestial movements of stars, planets, and other cosmic bodies. &#91;37&#93;

##### Virtues

According to *The Etymologies* of Isidore of Seville, the [Virtues](/Virtues_(angel)) are distinguished by their mastery over the elements. Beyond their role as agents of motion, they are also believed to influence and manage the natural forces, including phenomena like storms. &#91;37&#93; Furthermore, they are associated with the occurrence of miracles and are seen as encouraging humans to fortify their faith in [God](/God_in_Christianity). &#91;38&#93;

##### Powers or Authorities

In *The Etymologies* of Isidore of Seville, the [Powers](/Powers_(angel)), referred to in Latin as *potestas* (plural *potestates*) and in Greek as ἐξουσίαι (*exousiai*), &#91;38&#93; are so named due to their function as angels who wield authority over malevolent forces. It is their charge to restrain these evil influences, preventing them from inflicting harm. &#91;38&#93; The Powers also oversee the legitimate authority granted to earthly rulers, such as kings. &#91;37&#93;

#### Third Order

##### Principalities or Rulers

According to *The Etymologies* of Isidore of Seville, the [Principalities](/Principalities_(angel)), also translated as "Princedoms" or "Rulers" (from the Greek *archai*, see Greek root in Eph 3:10), are the angels tasked with the guidance and protection of nations and collective groups of people, as well as institutions like the Church. The Principalities are depicted as presiding over the various angelic choirs, assigning them their divine ministries. Within this order, some angels are administrators, while others serve in assisting roles. &#91;38&#93; &#91; *needs update* &#93;

An example of a Principality angel with a recognized veneration is the [Angel of Portugal](/Angel_of_Portugal).

##### Archangels

*   Main articles: [Archangel](/Archangel), [Gabriel](/Gabriel), [Michael (archangel)](/Michael_(archangel)), and [Raphael (archangel)](/Raphael_(archangel))

The term [archangel](/Archangel) appears in the [New Testament](/New_Testament) on only two occasions: in 1 Thessalonians 4:16 and Jude 1:9.

Across most Christian traditions, [Gabriel](/Gabriel) is also recognized as an archangel, though this designation lacks direct textual support within the scriptures. The term "archangel" itself is consistently used in the singular, never in the plural, and specifically refers to [Michael](/Michael_(archangel)).

The name of the archangel [Raphael](/Raphael_(archangel)) is found exclusively within the [Book of Tobit](/Book_of_Tobit) (also known as Tobias).

The [Holy See](/Holy_See), in its 2001 Directory on popular piety, issued a directive stating: "The practice of assigning names to the Holy Angels should be discouraged, except in the cases of Gabriel, Raphael and Michael whose names are contained in [Holy Scripture](/Catholic_Bible)." &#91;39&#93;

#### Guardian angels

*   Main article: [Guardian angel](/Guardian_angel)

*   This section, it must be said, is woefully lacking in the fundamental requirement of any credible article: citations. It makes claims about guardian angels without providing any [sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability) whatsoever. This deficiency must be rectified by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) to [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Angels_in_Christianity) . Failure to do so risks the removal of this material. (August 2025) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

A guardian angel is, by definition, a specific type of [angel](/Angel) designated to provide protection and guidance to an individual, a group, or even an entire nation. The concept of [tutelary beings](/Tutelary_deity) can be traced back through the annals of antiquity. The notion of angels watching over individuals played a significant role in [Ancient Judaism](/Judaism). Within [Christianity](/Christianity), the complex structure of the [hierarchy of angels](/Hierarchy_of_angels) was significantly elaborated upon in the 5th century by the influential [Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite](/Pseudo-Dionysius_the_Areopagite). The theological understanding of angels and tutelary spirits has continued to evolve since the 5th century. The core belief remains that guardian angels are divinely appointed to protect whomever [God](/God_in_Christianity) assigns them to. The Watchers are often considered to belong to this classification of angels.

